text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild]]%0a%0a!Scottish English in Media%0a%0a:Author: Thomas_H_K%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aAldi makes an ad mocking a Scottish accent. %0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aThe supermarket company Aldi published a series of radio advertisements in Australia which made fun of different languages and dialects. Although you can no longer find them online, several articles document the ad and backlash to it.%0a%0aOne ad opened with the sound of bagpipes, before a man's voice with a Scottish Accent introduced themselves as the head whiskey distiller for Aldi. As he continues, a woman with a standard British accent speaks over him,"translating" what he is saying. The 'translator' continues even as the distiller protests that they are speaking English.%0a%0aA complaint was filed to regulators that the ad perpetuated stereotypes that Scottish English was incomprehensible and speakers could not speak English. The board rejected the complaint on the grounds that the ad intended to be humorous and was mocking the translator as opposed to speaker.%0a%0aSome common features of Scottish English that the ad may have been mocking are the contrast between contrast /or/ and /ur/ - such as the distinction between 'floor' and 'flour' [pronounced as /flor/ and /flur/]. Other constructs is the lack of contrast between [æ] and [ɑ] and the [i] bring changed to an [e] at the end of sentences. Body is pronounced as 'bæde' instead of 'bɑdi.' Most common is the lengthening of vowels in certain situations (see below), such as before rhotics or fricatives. %0a%0aI also wanted to briefly note the use of Scottish English to impart prestige on the company's alcohol products as notable. %0a%0aSources:%0ahttps://www.thespiritsbusiness.com/2016/03/watchdog-rejects-complaint-about-racist-aldi-whisky-ad/%0ahttps://www.thenational.scot/news/14902122.aldis-scottish-accent-translation-ad-not-racist/%0ahttps://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scottish_vowel_length_rule%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: B:)%0a(:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild:)
